  "articleSummary": "This technical analysis argues that the traditional security model—treating production as dangerous and local environments as safe—is obsolete due to the rise of \"infostealers\" and agentic automation. The author contends that modern developer machines are \"credential warehouses\" vulnerable to non-traditional breaches like prompt injection, poisoned dependencies, and misconfigured CI/CD workflows (specifically GitHub Actions). Written in an urgent, cautionary tone, the article uses the framing device of \"the developer as the breach\" to highlight how routine actions—like granting an AI agent broad filesystem access or using mutable version tags—now constitute high-risk security failures. The intended audience is software engineers and DevOps professionals who must shift from defending against external \"malware\" to sandboxing their own tools and workflows.",
